SIMPLE: monogram
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Monogram
<hw>Mon"o*gram</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>monogramma</ets>; Gr. <grk>mo`nos</grk> single + <grk>gra`mma</grk>
letter, fr. <grk>gra`fein</grk> to write: cf. F. <ets>monogramme</ets>.
See <er>Graphic</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A character or cipher
composed of two or more letters interwoven or combined so as to
represent a name, or a part of it (usually the initials). Monograms are
often used on seals, ornamental pins, rings, buttons, and by painters,
engravers, etc., to distinguish their works.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><illust>Monogram.</illust>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ The monogram above, combining the letters of the name
<er>Karolvs</er>, was used by Charlemagne.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A picture in lines; a sketch.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>An arbitrary sign for a word.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>monogram</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: monogram
<hw>mon"o*gram</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To inscribe or
ornament with a monogram.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monogrammal</ent>⟦br⟧
